reviewText: a little bit more explanation is required. quiz is being asked from what is being narrated word by word. how can anyone remember all the narration.
​poorly matching slides and text. Tiresome, winded sounding voice over. The material itself is interesting though.
Didn't like David's modules; I felt that the powerpoint wasn't helpfull in understanding the topics fully.  His narrative and the visuals lack correlation.
The course is so mechanic, even the voices are digital and the shouting instructor follows the slides only.

L​ots of typos and grammatical errors. I made a lot of mistakes until I read along with the videos. Needs someone to go through and do a good proofreading. Other than that, it seemed like there were good points to be made and learned.  Occasionally, there were areas that seemed confusing - I would've liked more examples of the different analysis methods.
We need to have a source for revesion or if the slides where available to revise from it.
T​he course content is good, but not helpful unless there is a project to submit for review. This is not mentioned upfront for the course. Disappointed.

Content is well written and succinct.Quiz questions need some editing.  There were a few where it appears there was a coding or back end issue and you there's no "bubble" to select an answer.  I got feedback that one of my True/False answers was wrong. I selected "true" to a statement, and the feedback given exactly restated the statement above but indicated that "true" was incorrect.  I didn't really follow the logic here.Since this is a remotely moderated course, there should be a bigger effort up front for cleanly edited quizzes since 100% of the certificate is tied to those scores.
Mechanical presentation and reading of slides. A bit dry.
